description:

Fighting is escalating, forcing hundreds of thousands of civilians to flee their homes on both sides of the border

Chhean Vannarith. Chairman of Angkor Social Innovation Park and a former Assistant to Cambodia’s Defence Minister in 2011 and 2012.

description:
Clashes have been reported between the Syrian army and the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) in Aleppo.
Syria’s state-run SANA news agency reported on Monday that the SDF launched attacks against security force positions near the Sheihan and Lairmoun roundabouts in Aleppo.
“The Gaziantep-Aleppo road has been closed from the direction of the Lairmoun and Sheihan roundabouts as SDF targets the road,” the news agency said.
The clashes come as Turkish Foreign Minister Hakan Fidan visited Syria’s capital Damascus for talks on the integration of the SDF into the new Syrian army ahead of a looming deadline.
In March, Syrian President Ahmed al-Sharaa signed a deal with the SDF, which has controlled a large swath of territory in northeastern Syria, to integrate the group into the country’s state institutions.

Here to discuss the latest developments are Al Jazeera's Ayman Oghanna, live from Damascus, and Rob Geist Pinfold, a Lecturer in International Security at King's College London,

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Nuked is a powerful film that examines the hidden legacy of United States nuclear weapons testing on Bikini Atoll in the Pacific - and its people. Through moving testimonies, rare archive and expert insight, it reveals how these Marshall Islanders were uprooted from their home under the false promise they’d return, only to face radiation exposure, displacement and the loss of a centuries-old culture.

From the devastation of the US military's Operation Crossroads in 1946 to the islanders’ ongoing fight for recognition and justice, the film exposes government deception, biomedical experiments and a global pattern of Indigenous communities sacrificed in the cause of military ambition. Beyond the Pacific, the film traces parallel histories of nuclear testing across the world, its fallout crossing borders and generations. With climate change now threatening radioactive waste sites, this is a haunting history and a stark warning, a story the world cannot afford to forget.

#nuclearweapons
title: Nuked: once a paradise, now a nuclear wasteland | Featured Documentary

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Russian investigators say a senior military commander has been killed in a suspected car bomb attack in Moscow. Lieutenant General Fanil Sarvarov died when his vehicle exploded in the capital’s Yasenevo district.
Speaking to Al Jazeera, military analyst Marina Miron said the killing appears to be an assassination rather than a battlefield death.
She said Ukrainian security services would be capable of targeting senior Russian figures inside Russia.
Miron described Sarvarov as a key figure in training and preparing troops for the war in Ukraine.
She said eliminating such figures can weaken Russia at a strategic level and disrupt military planning.
Miron added that replacing an experienced general during an active war would be difficult.
She said the attack also sends a psychological message to Russia’s military leadership, creating fear among senior commanders.

The strike hit Al Harra market on Saturday in the town of Malha, which is controlled by the paramilitary Rapid Support Forces.
Sudan's army and the RSF have been locked in a conflict that's killed tens of thousands of people. 

The Sudan Doctors Network says the RSF has killed at least 16 people in Kordofan in the past two weeks.
It accuses the RSF and its allies of shelling residential areas in the town of Dilling.
Women, children and elderly people are among the dead.

More than a hundred thousand people have been killed in the conflict, which has displaced about 14 million.  
A UN report says at least 1,600 people, mainly women and children, are arriving in nearby White Nile state. 
They've escaped intensive fighting in western Kordofan. 

Al Jazeera’s Mohamed Vall reports from a camp for displaced people in White Nile state.

description:
Russian investigators say a senior army officer has been killed in a suspected car bomb attack in Moscow.
Lieutenant General Fanil Sarvarov died when his vehicle exploded in the capital’s Yasenevo district.
Images released by authorities show the wreckage of his car, as forensic teams search the blast site for evidence.
He was the head of the army's operational training directorate.

Al Jazeera’s Yulia Shapovalova has more from Moscow, Russia.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Thailand and Cambodia's foreign ministers are attending their first face-to-face talks since renewed fighting broke out two weeks ago. 
They're in Kuala Lumpur alongside other foreign ministers from the ASEAN regional bloc.
It's part of a renewed diplomatic effort to end the border conflict. 
Fighting has killed at least 60 people and displaced around 800,000 on both sides. 
The two countries accuse the other of violating a ceasefire they signed in October.

Al Jazeera’s Tony Cheng is in Bangkok, Thailand and Assed Baig is in Phnom Penh, Cambodia for the latest developments.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Dire living conditions are forcing thousands of desperate Rohingya Muslims to flee Myanmar and refugee camps in Bangladesh.
The United Nations says more than 5,300 Rohingya refugees attempted dangerous sea crossings in 2025, with women and children making up more than two-thirds.
At least 600 are reported dead or missing, as violence in Myanmar’s Rakhine State and cuts to US aid worsen conditions.
Until recently, the US has been the largest donor supporting Rohingya refugees, contributing nearly 300 million dollars last year, almost half of all funding.
But the US has drastically cut its humanitarian funding this year. Aid groups are warning that without urgent support, food rations will continue to be cut, putting a million people in danger.

Al Jazeera’s Tanvir Chowdhury has more from the refugee camp in Cox's Bazar, Bangladesh.
